<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-10-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-10-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="1189" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1189">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5293.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-10-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 20, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s October 19, 5 p.m. I have found no excitement concerning
                            arrival of <hi rend="italic">Des Moines</hi> except on the part of
                            administration, and I so informed Minister for Foreign Affairs just now.
                            He declared that the Government had no objection to the arrival of the
                            vessel now, but that there had been fears as to the effect which its
                            arrival would have at the outbreak of uprising at Vera Cruz.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>